res, compressing them and thereby \u2026\nOperation\nWhen one of the balls at the end (\"the first\") is pulled sideways, the attached string constrains it along an upward arc. When released it strikes the second ball and comes nearly, but not entirely, to a dead stop.\n\n## Relevant Context 4\nThis force pushes the last ball upward, causing it to swing back and strike the stationary balls, repeating the process. The motion of the balls can be visualized as a line of touching coins, where the energy is temporarily stored as potential energy in the compression of the material rather than being lost as heat. This principle is fundamental to understanding the conservation of energy and momentum in physical systems. Wikipedia\n+1\nRead more\nWikipedia\nNewton's cradle - Wikipedia\nNewton's cradle is a device, usually made of metal, that demonstrates the principles of conservation of momentum and conservation of energy in physics with swinging spheres. When o\u2026\nUniverse of Particles\nNewton\u2019s Cradle \u2013 Energy and Inertia | Universe of Particles\nThe strict particle model presented here makes no distinction between the subatomic level and macrolevel when it comes to motion. However, it does make two bold claims.\n"